    {
      "type": "context",
      "agent": "user",
      "content": "# ARCHITECT PLAN OVERVIEW\n**Plan**: Implement mandatory Google warmup phase before target crawl using camoufox-js\n**Description**: Add a warmup step in src/main.ts that launches a standalone Camoufox browser page (via src/warmup.ts), visits google.com, performs human-like interactions (typing, mouse moves, cookie dismissal) to warm the fingerprint, then closes the page before the actual crawling begins. Reuses existing proxy and launch options. No new dependencies needed.\n## All Steps\n1. **Create warmup function in src/warmup.ts**: ## Goal\n\nCreate a new module `src/warmup.ts` that exports an async function `warmupBrowser()`. This function launches a standalone Camoufox browser page, navigates to https://www.google.com, performs human-like interactions (typing, mouse movement, cookie dismissal), waits a short time, then closes the page and browser. The warmup must run **before** the actual crawling begins, ensuring the Camoufox fingerprint is “warm” and the proxy session is established, reducing detection risk.\n\n## Task Type\n\n**New file creation** – Write a self-contained async function that reuses existing Camoufox launch options and proxy configuration from `src/main.ts`. The function will be called from `main.ts` later, but in this step only the module is created.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n\n- **Entry point**: `src/main.ts` – reads input, creates `proxyConfiguration` (RESIDENTIAL, IT), instantiates `PlaywrightCrawler` with Camoufox `launchOptions`.\n- **Launch options** (lines ~148–160 of `main.ts`):\n  - `headless: true` (or controlled by input)\n  - `window: { width: 1280, height: 720 }`\n  - `proxy: proxyUrl` from proxyConfiguration\n  - `geoip: true`\n  - `locale: 'it-IT'`\n  - `humanize: true`\n  - `verbose: true` (sometimes)\n  - `blockAds: true`\n- These options are used when creating the crawler via `new PlaywrightCrawler({ launchContext: { launchOptions }, ... })`.\n- The warmup must use **the same Camoufox browser launch options** to maintain fingerprint consistency. The crawler’s `launchOptions` object is accessible; the warmup will need to accept it as a parameter.\n- No new npm dependencies are needed. The project already has `camoufox-js`, `playwright`, and `@crawlee/playwright`.\n- All browser automation must happen via Playwright API (Camoufox is a Playwright fork). Use `firefox.launch()` from `playwright` or the Camoufox equivalent. The project’s `launchOptions` includes `channel: ''` or similar; use `firefox.launch(launchOptions)`.\n- **Proxy**: The `proxyUrl` is passed in `launchOptions`. The warmup must accept an optional `proxyUrl` parameter (string) and include it in the launch options if provided.\n- Google interactions: navigate to `https://www.google.com`, wait for load, click the search box, type a random benign query (e.g., “Apify web scraping”), simulate typing delay, move mouse randomly, wait for results, dismiss cookie banner if present (`button:has-text('Accetta tutto')` or `button:has-text('Accept all')`), wait 2–3 seconds, then close the page and browser.\n- Use `apify/log` for logging (prefix with `[Warmup]`).\n\n## Action\n\n1. Create file `src/warmup.ts`.\n2. Export an async function with signature:\n   ```typescript\n   export async function warmupBrowser(launchOptions: any, proxyUrl?: string): Promise<void>\n   ```\n   - `launchOptions` is the Camoufox browser launch options object (as used in main.ts).\n   - `proxyUrl` is optional; if provided, it overrides or sets `launchOptions.proxy`.\n3. Inside `warmupBrowser`:\n   - Import `firefox` from `playwright` (or `camoufox-js` – verify which is correct; the project uses `@crawlee/playwright` which internally uses camoufox, but direct launch should use `playwright`). Use `import { firefox } from 'playwright';`.\n   - Merge `proxyUrl` into `launchOptions` if provided.\n   - Log `'[Warmup] Launching browser for warmup…'`.\n   - Launch browser: `const browser = await firefox.launch(launchOptions);`\n   - Create a new context: `const context = await browser.newContext({ viewport: { width: 1280, height: 720 } });`\n   - Create a page: `const page = await context.newPage();`\n   - Log `'[Warmup] Navigating to https://www.google.com'`.\n   - Go to Google: `await page.goto('https://www.google.com', { waitUntil: 'networkidle' });`\n   - Accept cookie consent if present (using Italian locale it might be Italian text – handle both Italian and English).\n   - Wait for search box selector: `input[name=\"q\"]`.\n   - Click on search box, type a query with realistic delays (`page.keyboard.type('Apify web scraping', { delay: 100 })`).\n   - Simulate mouse moves: `await page.mouse.move(100, 200); await page.wait(500);`\n   - Wait for results: `await page.waitForSelector('#search', { timeout: 5000 }).catch(() => {});`\n   - Wait an additional 2 seconds.\n   - Log `'[Warmup] Warmup complete, closing page…'`.\n   - Close page: `await page.close();`\n   - Close browser: `await browser.close();`\n4. Use `try/catch/finally` to ensure browser is always closed even on error.\n5. Log any errors at `warn` level but do not throw – warmup failure should not block the crawl. Log `'[Warmup] Failed but continuing: …'`.\n\n## Reasoning\n\n- Warmup is **mandatory** (not configurable) to improve stealth. By visiting a trusted site like Google with realistic interactions, the Camoufox fingerprint becomes stable and the proxy IP session is active before hitting target sites.\n- Using the same `launchOptions` ensures the browser configuration (window size, locale, humanization, proxy) is identical to the crawler, preventing fingerprint inconsistencies.\n- The function is standalone so it can be called from `main.ts` easily without modifying crawler internals.\n- Graceful error handling avoids aborting the crawl if Google is unreachable.\n\n## Implementation Details\n\n- **File**: `src/warmup.ts`\n- **Imports**:\n  ```typescript\n  import { firefox } from 'playwright';\n  import log from 'apify/log';\n  ```\n- **Function signature** as above.\n- Use `await page.waitForTimeout()` (or `page.wait(ms)` – Playwright 1.60 uses `page.waitForTimeout`).\n- Google cookie dismiss: try `button:has-text('Accetta tutto')` then `button:has-text('Accept all')`.\n- Typing: use `page.keyboard.type()` with delay.\n- Mouse move: use `page.mouse.move()` with random coordinates.\n- **No extra dependencies**.\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n\n- **Google not loading**: catch `TimeoutError` or other navigation errors, log warning, close browser, return normally. The crawl should proceed.\n- **Proxy errors**: if proxy fails, the warmup may fail; same handling – log warning, continue.\n- **Browser launch failure**: rare; log error and continue (crawler will launch its own browser later).\n- **Multiple warmups**: if called multiple times (not expected), each will launch a separate browser. OK.\n- **No proxyUrl provided**: use `launchOptions` as given (may already contain proxy from main.ts).\n\n## Validation\n\n- After implementation, verify the module can be imported without errors.\n- Run `npx tsx src/warmup.ts` (temporary test script) – should open and close Google successfully in headless mode.\n- Check that logs appear correctly with `[Warmup]` prefix.\n- Ensure no dangling browser processes remain after function returns (closed in `finally`).\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n\n- **Inputs**: `launchOptions` object (from main.ts), optional `proxyUrl` string.\n- **Dependencies**: `playwright` (already installed), `apify/log` (already installed).\n- **No new npm packages**.\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Must be ESM (type:module). Use `import` not `require`.\n- Follow project code style: single quotes, no `any` (use proper types from Playwright). For `launchOptions` use `import type { LaunchOptions } from 'playwright'`.\n- The function must **not** throw; any error must be caught and logged.\n- Keep code concise – no unnecessary abstractions.\n2. **Call warmup in main.ts before crawler.run**: ## Goal\nModify `src/main.ts` to import and call the `warmupBrowser` function (created in step `create-warmup-module`) **before** `crawler.run(startUrls)`. This ensures a mandatory Google warmup page with human-like interactions is executed on every Actor run, regardless of the input URLs.\n\n## Task Type\nCode modification – insert import, call site, and error handling in the existing entry point file `src/main.ts`.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n- `src/main.ts` (the only file to modify):\n  - Lines 148-160: PlaywrightCrawler instantiation with `camoufox-js` launch options, proxyConfiguration, hooks, router.\n  - Line 163 (approx): `await crawler.run(startUrls)` – the actual crawl start.\n  - Proxy is created from input (line 49-55): `Actor.createProxyConfiguration({ groups: ['RESIDENTIAL'], countryCode: 'IT' })` stored as `proxyConfiguration`.\n  - Import pattern: `import { /* symbols */ } from '@crawlee/playwright'` and `import { launchOptions } from './launch_options.js'` (or inline object).\n- `src/warmup.ts` (already created by previous step): exports `async function warmupBrowser(browserLaunchOptions: object, proxyUrl?: string): Promise<void>`.\n- The warmup module expects the same `launchOptions` object used for the crawler (camoufox-js config) and an optional proxy URL string (obtained from `proxyConfiguration.newUrl()`).\n\n## Action\n1. **Add import** at the top of `src/main.ts`:\n   ```typescript\n   import { warmupBrowser } from './warmup.js';\n   ```\n2. **Locate the insertion point**: immediately after the crawler is fully configured (after all hooks, before `await crawler.run(startUrls)`). In the current file, this is between the last `crawlerConfig` line and `await crawler.run(...)`.\n3. **Obtain a proxy URL** for the warmup page:\n   - The `proxyConfiguration` object is already available in scope.\n   - Use `const proxyUrl = await proxyConfiguration.newUrl();` to get a fresh proxy URL (same residential pool).\n4. **Insert the warmup call** with error handling:\n   ```typescript\n   // --- WARMUP PHASE: Google warmup for fingerprint priming ---\n   log.info('Starting mandatory warmup phase (Google interactions)');\n   try {\n       const warmupProxyUrl = await proxyConfiguration.newUrl();\n       await warmupBrowser(launchOptions, warmupProxyUrl);\n       log.info('Warmup completed successfully');\n   } catch (warmupError) {\n       log.warning('Warmup failed but continuing with target crawl', { error: warmupError.message });\n       // Warmup failure should not block crawling\n   }\n   ```\n   - Use `log` from `apify/log` (already imported).\n5. **Ensure no duplicate proxy call**: If `proxyConfiguration.newUrl()` is already called elsewhere (e.g., inside crawler config), it’s fine; each call returns a different sub-resident URL.\n6. **Preserve the existing `crawler.run` call** unchanged.\n\n## Reasoning\n- Placing warmup **after** crawler creation ensures browser launch options are final and consistent between warmup and actual crawling.\n- Using the same `proxyConfiguration` ensures the warmup page appears from the same IP class (Italian residential) as the subsequent crawl, avoiding sudden IP changes that could raise suspicion.\n- The try-catch prevents a warmup failure (e.g., network error, Google block) from aborting the entire Actor run; the target crawl will still proceed.\n- The call uses `await`, so the Actor pauses until warmup finishes (or fails), maintaining linear orchestration.\n\n## Implementation Details\n- **File**: `src/main.ts`\n- **Insert at**: line 162 (after crawler config block, before the `await crawler.run(startUrls)` line). Exact line number may vary; insert logically between the two blocks.\n- **No other files need changes**: `src/routes.ts`, `.actor/input_schema.json`, `Dockerfile`, `package.json` remain untouched.\n- **Imports to add**: `import { warmupBrowser } from './warmup.js';`\n- **Variables used**: `proxyConfiguration` (already in scope), `launchOptions` (already in scope), `log` (via `apify/log`).\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- If `proxyConfiguration.newUrl()` throws (e.g., proxy pool exhausted), catch it and fall back to no proxy (undefined) – optional but safe.\n- If `warmupBrowser` throws (network timeout, Google captcha, etc.), log a warning and continue – the main crawl is not affected.\n- If the Actor is aborting during warmup (`Actor.on('aborting')`), the warmup function should check the abort signal and clean up promptly (handled internally by warmup module).\n- The warmup page is closed inside `warmupBrowser`, so no resource leak.\n\n## Validation\n1. Run `npm test` (Vitest) – existing integration test in `test/main.test.ts` must pass unchanged.\n2. Run the Actor locally with `tsx src/main.ts --input='{\"startUrls\":[{\"url\":\"https://apify.com\"}],\"maxRequestsPerCrawl\":5}'` – verify in logs that \"Starting mandatory warmup phase\" appears, followed by warmup completion (or warning).\n3. Check that the warmup page actually reached Google (e.g., add a temporary `page.screenshot` for debugging, then remove).\n4. Ensure no new TypeScript/ESLint errors (`npm run lint`).\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- **Requires**: `src/warmup.ts` already created (step `create-warmup-module`) with exported `warmupBrowser`.\n- **Uses**: `proxyConfiguration` from `Actor.createProxyConfiguration(...)` in `main.ts`.\n- **No new npm packages** – all dependencies already installed.\n\n## Constraints\n- The warmup must be **unconditional** – always runs, no opt-out.\n- The warmup must reuse the **exact same Camoufox launch options** as the main crawler (stealth settings, window size, locale, etc.).\n- The warmup must **not** modify any global state (session pool, request queue) that would corrupt the subsequent crawl.\n- The warmup must complete within a reasonable time (default 30-second timeout recommended inside `warmupBrowser`).\n3. **Add warmup test cases in test/main.test.ts**: Step details are being generated.\n4. **Execute full test suite to verify integration**: Step details are being generated.",
